      "name": "In-vitro hemolysis experimental dataset (2024)",
      "description": "Plasma-free haemoglobin measurements from in-vitro loop experiments across 5 flow-speed operating points used for model validation.",
      "dataVintage": "2024-11-05T00:00:00Z"
    }
  ],
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/hemolysis-loop-vr-01",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "In-vitro hemolysis loop validation — 5 operating points",
      "description": "CFD-predicted normalised index of hemolysis compared against plasma-free haemoglobin measurements across 5 flow-speed combinations. Mean absolute error 12% across operating points; Monte Carlo 95% prediction intervals bracket all experimental means."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/velocity-piv-vr-02",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "PIV velocity field validation — impeller exit plane",
      "description": "Particle image velocimetry measurements at impeller exit compared to CFD velocity predictions. Normalised RMS error 8.3% across the measurement plane."
    }
  ],
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver must have documented unit-test suite, regression testing, and configuration-management records covering the version used for production runs.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2023R2 has documented regression tests and ISO 9001 quality management. Configuration management records exist but do not fully cover all user-defined function (UDF) subroutines implementing the hemolysis power-law model, leaving a gap at Gradation 3 versus the required Gradation 4."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Order-of-accuracy tests against analytic solutions for all governing equations, including the hemolysis transport scalar.",
      "rationale": "Order-of-accuracy verified for Navier-Stokes and energy equations via Method of Manufactured Solutions. Hemolysis scalar transport UDF verified only against a simplified 1-D benchmark; full 3-D MMS not completed, limiting achievement to Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Richardson extrapolation on at least three systematically refined meshes with GCI reported for hemolysis index and velocity at impeller exit.",
      "rationale": "Three mesh levels (4.2 M, 11.8 M, 28.6 M cells) used; GCI for velocity 2.1%. GCI for hemolysis index 9.4%, exceeding the 5% target. Spatial discretization error remains a gap for the primary QoI."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions must replicate COU operating envelope within specified tolerances; temperature, hematocrit, and anticoagulant protocol documented.",
      "rationale": "Temperature controlled to 37 ± 0.5 °C; hematocrit 33 ± 2%. Anticoagulant protocol documented. However, in-vitro loop compliance (pressure-volume relationship) not characterised, introducing uncertainty in effective operating point at highest flow rate."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative metric (e.g., E_rel or MAPE) with uncertainty bounds reported for each QoI; systematic bias assessed.",
      "rationale": "MAPE 12% for hemolysis index across 5 operating points; 95% CI brackets all experimental means. Systematic over-prediction at low-flow conditions (+18%) not fully explained; bias correction not applied, limiting achievement to Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs used in validation directly map to clinical decision threshold (absolute NIH); surrogate QoIs justified if direct measurement unavailable.",
      "rationale": "Normalised index of hemolysis (NIH) is the primary clinical QoI and is directly measured and predicted. Shear stress exposure time used as intermediate QoI; mapping to NIH relies on Giersiepen power-law coefficients not updated since 2004, reducing relevance score."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments conducted at COU flow-speed combinations; geometry identical to COU device; patient-representative blood analogue used.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry matching COU. Five operating points span COU envelope. Porcine blood used rather than human blood analogue; species difference in red cell fragility introduces relevance gap."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence demonstrated via residual and QoI monitors; round-off and iterative errors bounded.",
      "rationale": "Residuals converge to 1e-6 for continuity and momentum. Hemolysis scalar residual plateaus at 1e-4 for two operating points; iterative error contribution to hemolysis index estimated at 3–5%, not formally bounded per ASME V&V 20."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation plan reviewed by independent analyst; boundary condition setup and post-processing scripts version-controlled and peer-reviewed.",
      "rationale": "Simulation plan reviewed internally. Boundary condition setup scripts are version-controlled; post-processing scripts for hemolysis integration are not under formal version control and were not independently reviewed, creating a use-error risk at the integration step."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Turbulence model and hemolysis constitutive model selection justified by literature and sensitivity study; non-Newtonian rheology model validated.",
      "rationale": "SST k-omega turbulence model selected; sensitivity to turbulence model not assessed. Giersiepen power-law hemolysis model used without comparison to alternative (e.g., Taskin) model. Non-Newtonian Carreau model applied but not independently validated for this pump geometry. Significant model-form uncertainty remains unquantified."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All boundary condition datasets traceable to current model revision; input uncertainty propagated via Monte Carlo; rheological parameters characterised for the blood analogue used in COU.",
      "rationale": "Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification performed on inlet velocity and rotational speed. Rheological boundary conditions (viscosity, Carreau parameters) sourced from a 2018 characterisation study predating the January 2026 model revision by approximately eight years. Blood rheology is known to vary with donor population and storage conditions; the 2018 dataset reflects a prior experimental campaign and has not been re-characterised against the current porcine blood lot used in 2024–2025 validation experiments. No re-validation of input parameters against the updated model build was performed or documented."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Sufficient replicates to characterise experimental variability; sample-to-sample variability in blood properties reported.",
      "rationale": "Three replicate runs per operating point; coefficient of variation in NIH 8–14%. Sample-to-sample hematocrit variability documented. Donor-to-donor variability in red cell fragility not characterised across replicates, limiting statistical power for the primary QoI."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Input parameters in simulation match experimental conditions within stated tolerances; any deviations justified and sensitivity assessed.",
      "rationale": "Rotational speed matched to ±0.5 RPM; flow rate to ±2%. Inlet temperature boundary condition set to 37 °C matching experiment. Rheological parameters in the CFD model derived from the 2018 dataset rather than from the 2024–2025 experimental blood lots, creating a parameter equivalency gap between simulation inputs and the actual test fluid properties."
    }
  ],
